## Intent

> Load and sanity-check the raw FY2025 daily sales data
>
> Do steps 1 and 2 of the Sales MIS Workflow this cycle only: load the raw workbook and run the sanity check it describes. Stop once the clean staged dataset and the anomaly report are written -- the dashboard is a later cycle's job.

Context:

- raw_source_workbook: uploads/bank_daily_sales_2025.xlsx
- staged_dataset_output: workspace/staged_daily_sales.csv
- anomaly_report_output: workspace/anomaly_report.md

## Decision

> Steps 1 and 2 of the Sales MIS Workflow are complete for this cycle. Both outputs are written and verified.
>
> **What was done, per the MIS manual:**
>
> **Status: validated.**
>
> Per the intent, work stops here — the dashboard (Steps 3 and 4) is a later cycle's job.
>
> One item worth flagging for the next cycle's operator: the 55 no-data calendar days are reported as a coverage gap. If FY2025 daily sales were only expected on business days, most of these are weekends/holidays and are benign; if daily coverage was expected, they warrant investigation before the dashboard is built. The report states the fact without assuming which is the case.
> **Step 1 (Load).** Read the raw workbook `uploads/bank_daily_sales_2025.xlsx` — sheet "Daily Sales Data", range A1:Q908. Loading was combined with an immediate sanity check so any schema change or corrupt extract is caught before anything downstream trusts the file (§ Section 1).
> **Step 2 (Sanity-check), following § Section 2 with dynamic, relative ranges** — the header row and last data row were located by inspecting the sheet, not by assuming a fixed count:
> **Schema:** all five expected concepts are present (Date→Date, branch→Branch Code, product→Product Category, channel→Channel, rm→RM Name), plus the full 17-column set. No schema anomaly.
> **Count / calendar coverage:** 907 data rows spanning 2025-01-01 to 2025-12-31 (365 calendar days). **55 calendar days have no rows** — this gap is named in the anomaly report, not silently ignored.
> **Nulls:** the two formula columns (Account Achievement %, Amount Achievement %) carried no cached value, exactly as the manual anticipates for Excel formula columns; their achievement-percent values were **recomputed from the raw counts** (actual/target) rather than being flagged as nulls. No other null columns found.
> **Duplicates:** none on the key (date, branch, product, channel, RM).
> **Outputs written and verified on disk:**
> `workspace/staged_daily_sales.csv` — the clean staged dataset, 907 rows + header (908 lines), all anomalies named rather than dropped, formula columns filled with recomputed values. This is the file the next step reads.
> `workspace/anomaly_report.md` — schema / count / nulls / duplicates sections, with the 55 calendar gaps and the formula-column recomputation documented.

## Explanation

> Steps 1 and 2 of the Sales MIS Workflow — loading and sanity-checking the raw sales workbook — were completed and validated, producing a clean staged dataset (`staged_daily_sales.csv`) and an accompanying `anomaly_report.md`, both verified on disk, with all anomalies documented rather than silently dropped. Work correctly stopped here because the dashboard (Steps 3 and 4) belongs to a later cycle, and the one open item — 55 calendar days with no sales data — was flagged for the next operator to interpret as either benign (weekends/holidays) or worth investigating, depending on whether daily coverage was expected.

